1
00:00:09,076 --> 00:00:11,278
[children yelling]

2
00:00:18,352 --> 00:00:21,421
<i> ♪♪ [orchestra]</i>

3
00:00:49,449 --> 00:00:51,084
Come on. Right here.

4
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:16,076
[Boy]
Hey, Joey! It's your brother!

5
00:01:21,648 --> 00:01:24,351
[Man]
There he is!
There's the guy!

6
00:01:24,351 --> 00:01:26,586
Hey!
Ah, how you
doin', buddy?

7
00:01:26,586 --> 00:01:28,588
[all chattering]

8
00:01:28,588 --> 00:01:30,390
Playin' ball?
Yeah!

9
00:01:30,390 --> 00:01:32,759
Want to play ball?
Can I play ball with you guys?
Yeah!

10
00:01:32,759 --> 00:01:36,430
Oh, all right!
Let's play some baseball.
All right.

11
00:01:36,430 --> 00:01:38,865
Okay, Joey?
You ready, buddy? Okay.

12
00:01:38,865 --> 00:01:40,934
Here we go.

13
00:01:40,934 --> 00:01:43,637
There it is! Okay,
go now, go, start runnin'!

14
00:01:43,637 --> 00:01:46,773
Here we go! You're comin' in,
you're comin' home!

15
00:01:46,773 --> 00:01:48,675
There it is!
Perfect, perfect!

16
00:01:48,675 --> 00:01:51,778
Throw it back to Bob.
First base, over there.

17
00:01:51,778 --> 00:01:53,480
All right, Joey.
Here he comes now!

18
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:54,748
Joey!
Run him down, run him down!

19
00:01:56,883 --> 00:01:59,186
Yeah, that's it!

20
00:01:59,186 --> 00:02:01,521
That's how it's done.
That's excellent.

21
00:02:03,256 --> 00:02:05,425
Come here, all right!
That's the way it's done.

22
00:02:07,661 --> 00:02:09,763
You guys understand
everything was explaining?

23
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:15,402
Come on, Ma!
We're gonna be late!

24
00:02:15,402 --> 00:02:17,804
Come on!

25
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:20,207
I'm coming.
Jesus, Mary and Joseph.

26
00:02:20,207 --> 00:02:21,942
Do you have all the tickets
and everything?

27
00:02:21,942 --> 00:02:24,645
How's your face?
Let me see that face.

28
00:02:24,645 --> 00:02:26,780
Mrs. Vancucco, remember
today's the day!

29
00:02:26,780 --> 00:02:28,982
We're gonna win this game,
I just know it!

30
00:02:28,982 --> 00:02:31,451
[Man]
Get your programs!

31
00:02:31,451 --> 00:02:34,888
1957 World Series Programs!

32
00:02:34,888 --> 00:02:37,224
<i>[Announcer]</i>
<i>...New York, to open</i>
<i>the World Series,</i>

33
00:02:37,224 --> 00:02:39,493
<i>against</i>
<i>the heavily-favored Yankees,</i>

34
00:02:39,493 --> 00:02:42,529
<i>led by Henry Aaron,</i>
<i>Eddie Matthews,</i>

35
00:02:42,529 --> 00:02:44,631
<i>and Brooklyn's</i>
<i>own Frank Torre,</i>

36
00:02:44,631 --> 00:02:49,669
<i>the Braves are looking</i>
<i>for their first World Series</i>
<i>title since 1914.</i>

37
00:02:49,669 --> 00:02:51,938
What's the name?
Tickets for Torre,
Joe and Margaret.

38
00:02:51,938 --> 00:02:53,006
Joe and Margaret Torre!

39
00:02:53,006 --> 00:02:54,741
You related to Frank?

40
00:02:54,741 --> 00:02:56,843
Yeah, he's my brother!
And I'm his mother.

41
00:02:56,843 --> 00:02:58,745
Pleased to meet ya.
You don't think Frank

42
00:02:58,745 --> 00:03:00,781
can hit off
Whitey Ford, do ya?

43
00:03:00,781 --> 00:03:03,550
Hey, just wait and watch.
[laughs]

44
00:03:08,588 --> 00:03:10,190
Come on, Eddie!

45
00:03:13,994 --> 00:03:18,265
Hey, looks good!
<i> [Stadium announcer]</i>
<i> Number 24, Henry Aaron!</i>

46
00:03:18,265 --> 00:03:22,769
<i>At first base, number 14,</i>

47
00:03:22,769 --> 00:03:24,905
<i> Frank Torre!</i>

48
00:03:45,992 --> 00:03:49,296
You wanted to see me,
Mr. Cashin?

49
00:03:49,296 --> 00:03:51,531
I don't know how
to say this, Joe.

50
00:03:51,531 --> 00:03:54,000
We're looking to go
in a different direction.

51
00:03:58,638 --> 00:04:00,373
I don't know how
to tell you this, Joe.

52
00:04:00,373 --> 00:04:02,542
We're gonna be going
in a different direction.

53
00:04:12,319 --> 00:04:15,956
Pack up your things, Joe.
We're going in
a different direction.

54
00:04:49,623 --> 00:04:52,058
So? Change much?

55
00:04:52,058 --> 00:04:53,727
It's smaller.

56
00:04:53,727 --> 00:04:56,129
Hey, Joey! Gotcha!
Surprise, Joey!

57
00:04:56,129 --> 00:04:58,665
Surprise!
Well, hey.

58
00:04:58,665 --> 00:05:01,701
[excited chattering]

59
00:05:01,701 --> 00:05:04,137
Hey, what are you doing?
Leaving the baby out here?

60
00:05:04,137 --> 00:05:06,973
[all chattering]

61
00:05:08,842 --> 00:05:10,677
Surprise!
Joe looks great!

62
00:05:10,677 --> 00:05:12,746
Oh, he looks beautiful.
Look at this!
Here you go!

63
00:05:12,746 --> 00:05:14,381
And you, look at you!

64
00:05:16,950 --> 00:05:18,852
So wonderful
to have you back!

65
00:05:18,852 --> 00:05:22,088
Okay, let's get a picture!
Let's get a picture! Get closer.

66
00:05:22,088 --> 00:05:23,857
All right. Hey!
Come on!

67
00:05:23,857 --> 00:05:26,626
Just got to pull the plug.
Two, three, provolone!

68
00:05:26,626 --> 00:05:28,628
[laughing]

69
00:05:28,628 --> 00:05:31,998
Did you do this?
Are you responsible for that?
Yes, I am.

70
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:34,868
♪♪ [accordion]

71
00:05:40,006 --> 00:05:42,142
[Old Frank]
Yeah, she sang that for you,
she didn't sing it for me.

72
00:05:42,142 --> 00:05:45,011
Because Poppy's tall,
and you're small.
Because I was the baby.

73
00:05:45,011 --> 00:05:46,146
Yeah!
[laughing]

74
00:05:46,146 --> 00:05:48,348
She spoiled ya, Joe.
She spoiled you.

75
00:05:51,418 --> 00:05:54,054
Joey. Joey, Joey,
I got to tell you.

76
00:05:54,054 --> 00:05:57,123
I think you're
out of your mind.
Frankie, leave him alone.

77
00:05:57,123 --> 00:05:59,626
Why are you bothering him?
He just got here!

78
00:05:59,626 --> 00:06:01,828
I'm not bothering him!
Joey--

79
00:06:01,828 --> 00:06:05,832
Come on, you got a wife.
You got a kid on the way.

80
00:06:05,832 --> 00:06:08,868
Why are you doing this?
I thought it was over.

81
00:06:08,868 --> 00:06:11,905
I got a shot now.
I gotta take it.

82
00:06:11,905 --> 00:06:13,874
You come home!

83
00:06:13,874 --> 00:06:17,043
I don't think they realize
he's a grown man.

84
00:06:17,043 --> 00:06:19,713
Hey, it's the law
of the neighborhood.
They never grow up.

85
00:06:19,713 --> 00:06:21,815
They just get taller!

86
00:06:33,827 --> 00:06:36,029
Is he all right?

87
00:06:42,168 --> 00:06:44,838
You okay?
Hey, Rocco.

88
00:06:44,838 --> 00:06:49,743
[chuckles]
Yeah. Just sittin'
down for a minute.

89
00:06:49,743 --> 00:06:52,479
Hey, come on. Don't make
a Federal case out of it.
I'm okay.

90
00:06:52,479 --> 00:06:55,482
♪♪ [Italian accordion]
Martinez is fine.
But he's no Mattingly.

91
00:06:55,482 --> 00:06:58,785
I'll tell you what you
got to do. You gotta
bat Boggs leadoff.

92
00:06:58,785 --> 00:07:00,820
It don't matter
who bats leadoff.

93
00:07:00,820 --> 00:07:02,889
What you need
is more pitching. Now.

94
00:07:02,889 --> 00:07:05,825
Who you got after Cone?
I'm just about getting into it,

95
00:07:05,825 --> 00:07:08,094
but I think we got
a pretty solid staff.

96
00:07:08,094 --> 00:07:11,798
Joey, the man canned
Billy Martin 12 times.

97
00:07:11,798 --> 00:07:16,836
Bob Lemon. Lou Piniella--
He fires everybody!

98
00:07:16,836 --> 00:07:18,705
It's his team, I guess
he can do what he wants.

99
00:07:18,705 --> 00:07:21,875
Joey! Do you and Ali
have a place to live yet?

100
00:07:21,875 --> 00:07:23,777
Well, she's starting to look.

101
00:07:23,777 --> 00:07:25,745
You buying or renting?
Buying?

102
00:07:25,745 --> 00:07:27,514
You'll be out of
here by August!

103
00:07:27,514 --> 00:07:29,749
Joey, rent.

104
00:07:29,749 --> 00:07:34,521
I'm not interested
in honorable finishes,
or close seconds.

105
00:07:34,521 --> 00:07:39,059
This is New York!
I've won a few
World Series, Joe.

106
00:07:39,059 --> 00:07:42,862
And I think I have
a pretty good idea
what it takes:

107
00:07:42,862 --> 00:07:45,265
Focus. Dedication.

108
00:07:45,265 --> 00:07:48,001
The right people.
They produce,

109
00:07:48,001 --> 00:07:50,770
or you replace them
with people that will produce!

110
00:07:50,770 --> 00:07:54,174
If there's anything
you need, you let me know,
or you let Bob know.

111
00:07:55,542 --> 00:07:58,545
All you got to do
is win.

112
00:07:58,545 --> 00:08:00,180
That's what I came here
to do, George.

113
00:08:00,180 --> 00:08:02,182
Fine. Fine.

114
00:08:02,182 --> 00:08:05,852
I've been divorced twice
and fired three times.

115
00:08:05,852 --> 00:08:07,954
You never get used to it.

116
00:08:07,954 --> 00:08:10,223
Look at this.
Oh, my God, Joey!

117
00:08:10,223 --> 00:08:14,227
[Frank laughing]

118
00:08:14,227 --> 00:08:16,029
<i>[Radio announcer]</i>
<i>We're on the air.</i>
<i>What do you want to talk about?</i>

119
00:08:16,029 --> 00:08:17,297
<i>[Caller]</i>
<i>What do I want to talk about?</i>

120
00:08:17,297 --> 00:08:19,032
<i>What do you think</i>
<i>I want to talk about?</i>

121
00:08:19,032 --> 00:08:21,234
<i>The one thing</i>
<i>I'll give George credit for,</i>

122
00:08:21,234 --> 00:08:25,238
<i>maybe he drives people</i>
<i>crazy, but the man don't</i>
<i>sit still for losers!</i>

123
00:08:25,238 --> 00:08:28,308
<i>He's giving Torre a shot,</i>
<i>fine. But unless he delivers--</i>

124
00:08:28,308 --> 00:08:31,111
<i>[Announcer]</i>
<i>Tony from Tenafly.</i>
<i>You're on the air.</i>

125
00:08:31,111 --> 00:08:32,979
<i>[Tony from Tenafly]</i>
<i>Hey, I'm happy for Joe, right?</i>

126
00:08:32,979 --> 00:08:36,049
<i>He's a New York guy,</i>
<i>he's got a new baby, great!</i>

127
00:08:36,049 --> 00:08:38,017
<i>I give him April,</i>
<i>I give him May.</i>

128
00:08:38,017 --> 00:08:42,922
<i>By June he's gone.</i>
<i>Baby or no baby. End of story.</i>

129
00:08:42,922 --> 00:08:45,892
She's beautiful, Dad.
She's beautiful.

130
00:08:45,892 --> 00:08:47,794
Yeah, Joe, Joe!

131
00:08:47,794 --> 00:08:49,796
You didn't win with the Mets,
you didn't win with the Braves.

132
00:08:49,796 --> 00:08:53,066
You didn't win
with the Cardinals.
What's different now?

133
00:08:53,066 --> 00:08:56,169
This time it's the Yankees.
[laughter]

134
00:08:56,169 --> 00:09:00,907
Next month, I'm gonna be 65.
I think that had
a lot to do with it.

135
00:09:00,907 --> 00:09:03,943
Sixty-four years old,
and I never earned a nickel

136
00:09:03,943 --> 00:09:05,979
in all those years
that didn't come from baseball.

137
00:09:05,979 --> 00:09:09,048
When I was a kid,
I didn't have a paper route,
anything like that.

138
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:10,617
I was playing ball.

139
00:09:10,617 --> 00:09:13,153
Day after I graduated,
I went to play A Ball.

140
00:09:13,153 --> 00:09:16,222
Seventeen, I was
playing professional ball.
[laughs]

141
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:19,826
You know, I can tell you
what I did...

142
00:09:19,826 --> 00:09:23,296
every 4th of July
from 1948 to 1995.

143
00:09:23,296 --> 00:09:27,267
I was at a ball game!
[snickers]

144
00:09:27,267 --> 00:09:30,070
Every Memorial Day:
at a ball game.

145
00:09:30,070 --> 00:09:31,337
Every Labor Day:
at a ball game.

146
00:09:31,337 --> 00:09:34,841
At a ball game!
At a ball game!

147
00:09:34,841 --> 00:09:36,609
So what happened?
Why'd you quit?

148
00:09:37,644 --> 00:09:39,879
Too many ball games.

149
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:42,649
[laughs]

150
00:09:44,117 --> 00:09:46,286
Well, how do you feel about it?
You sorry you quit?

151
00:09:46,286 --> 00:09:48,655
Well, am I sorry I quit?

152
00:09:48,655 --> 00:09:50,857
The last six months
have been heaven!

153
00:09:50,857 --> 00:09:53,193
Last six months
have been heaven.

154
00:09:53,193 --> 00:09:55,161
[laughs]

155
00:09:57,363 --> 00:10:01,000
Because if you're interested
in some more ball games...

156
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:03,002
I'd like to hire you
as my bench coach.

157
00:10:04,003 --> 00:10:06,039
All right, wait a minute.

158
00:10:06,039 --> 00:10:07,941
Did George put you up to this?

159
00:10:07,941 --> 00:10:11,878
Don, this is my idea.

160
00:10:12,979 --> 00:10:15,682
Well, it's a damn good idea.

161
00:10:18,451 --> 00:10:21,054
Great.
Good.

162
00:10:21,054 --> 00:10:24,023
Well, guess what, ladies?

163
00:10:24,023 --> 00:10:26,693
You know, when I think about it,
it's really kind of amazing.

164
00:10:26,693 --> 00:10:29,162
My second season
with Milwaukee, what happens?

165
00:10:29,162 --> 00:10:31,931
I make it to the World Series.
Took it for granted.

166
00:10:31,931 --> 00:10:34,000
I said, "Well, this is
the way it's supposed to be."

167
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,468
Easiest thing
in the world, right?

168
00:10:35,468 --> 00:10:38,438
Yeah! I was arrogant.

169
00:10:38,438 --> 00:10:41,908
What the hell did I know,
that most Major Leaguers
never get a shot like that?

170
00:10:43,009 --> 00:10:44,377
I waited all my life for that.

171
00:10:44,377 --> 00:10:46,312
That's what I'm sayin'.

172
00:10:46,312 --> 00:10:47,947
What?

173
00:10:49,115 --> 00:10:52,218
Joey...
You're gonna do it.

174
00:10:53,920 --> 00:10:59,058
I won a batting title once.
Most Valuable Player once.

175
00:10:59,058 --> 00:11:02,061
But when you're an athlete,
you play to win.

176
00:11:02,061 --> 00:11:03,429
Win.

177
00:11:03,429 --> 00:11:06,065
In baseball, that means
the World Series.

178
00:11:06,065 --> 00:11:09,068
I played 2,209
baseball games,

179
00:11:09,068 --> 00:11:11,070
and never made it
to the World Series.

180
00:11:11,070 --> 00:11:16,009
I managed 1,901 games,
and never made it
to the World Series.

181
00:11:16,009 --> 00:11:18,211
I played 18 years as a player,

182
00:11:18,211 --> 00:11:20,213
19 years as a manager,

183
00:11:20,213 --> 00:11:22,115
never made it
to the World Series.

184
00:11:22,115 --> 00:11:23,950
Some guy looked it up,
and it turns out

185
00:11:23,950 --> 00:11:27,220
that I'm the one who spent
more days in a baseball uniform

186
00:11:27,220 --> 00:11:30,123
than anyone else in
the history of the game...

187
00:11:30,123 --> 00:11:32,158
who never made it
to the World Series.

188
00:11:32,158 --> 00:11:35,395
Now, how the hell
would you like to have
that on your epitaph?

189
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:49,309
[softly]
You know, this is not just
some kid with a couple years,

190
00:11:49,309 --> 00:11:52,345
that's your boy--
this is Dwight Gooden, skipper.

191
00:11:52,345 --> 00:11:53,780
Dwight Gooden!
Yeah, I know.

192
00:11:53,780 --> 00:11:56,449
Was he a great pitcher?
Yeah, sure.

193
00:11:56,449 --> 00:11:59,319
Was he a great pitcher?
This is what I got to know.

194
00:11:59,319 --> 00:12:01,821
Well, this is one
of the premier pictures
of all times.

195
00:12:01,821 --> 00:12:05,325
Yeah, I know what.
Listen: what about
the drug suspensions?

196
00:12:05,325 --> 00:12:08,228
He's clean now.
You know this?

197
00:12:08,228 --> 00:12:11,798
Absolutely.
Hmm.

198
00:12:11,798 --> 00:12:13,566
You know, he hasn't pitched
in a year and a half.

199
00:12:13,566 --> 00:12:18,271
Joe, this is a guy
that really wants
to make it back.

200
00:12:18,271 --> 00:12:22,141
Bottom line, Joe T.
The boss wants this guy.

201
00:12:22,141 --> 00:12:24,510
Are you going
to use him or not?

202
00:12:39,425 --> 00:12:41,294
Don't worry about it, Doc.
It's only spring training.

203
00:12:44,263 --> 00:12:46,265
[bat hits ball]

204
00:12:55,041 --> 00:12:58,778
All right.
Still spring training.
There's two weeks to go.

205
00:13:05,551 --> 00:13:07,787
You'll get him next time.
It's only spring training.

206
00:13:11,591 --> 00:13:14,327
I've lost Mélido Pérez.
He's gone for the season.

207
00:13:17,430 --> 00:13:21,601
Jimmy Key has had surgery.
It takes a whole year
to come back from that one.

208
00:13:21,601 --> 00:13:24,504
Kenny Rogers is banged
all over the place.

209
00:13:24,504 --> 00:13:26,639
And Andy Pettitte
is inexperienced,

210
00:13:26,639 --> 00:13:29,208
and that is four out of
my five starting pitchers.

211
00:13:29,208 --> 00:13:30,643
What about Doc Gooden?

212
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:32,445
Doc Gooden.

213
00:13:32,445 --> 00:13:34,447
He's a good pitcher,
isn't he?

214
00:13:34,447 --> 00:13:36,582
1986, he was a great pitcher.

215
00:13:36,582 --> 00:13:39,585
How they going?

216
00:13:39,585 --> 00:13:41,354
Great. Almost ready.

217
00:13:41,354 --> 00:13:43,890
Not the hamburgers,
the team!

218
00:13:43,890 --> 00:13:46,092
Great.

219
00:13:46,092 --> 00:13:48,294
Almost ready.

220
00:13:52,265 --> 00:13:53,566
<i>[Radio announcer]</i>
<i>Sal from the Bronx--</i>
<i>you're on the air!</i>

221
00:13:53,566 --> 00:13:55,501
<i>What's on your mind?</i>

222
00:13:55,501 --> 00:13:58,204
<i>[Sal]</i>
<i>Are you kidding?</i>
<i>It's gonna be a long year!</i>

223
00:13:58,204 --> 00:14:00,440
<i>And I don't mean</i>
<i>into October!</i>

224
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:02,608
<i>It's simple!</i>
<i>It's so simple!</i>

225
00:14:02,608 --> 00:14:06,479
<i>You know it, I know it,</i>
<i>everybody knows it</i>
<i>except Clueless Joe!</i>

226
00:14:06,479 --> 00:14:10,116
<i>The Yankees got no pitching.</i>
<i>None, zip, zilch, nada.</i>

227
00:14:10,116 --> 00:14:12,385
<i>[Tony from Tenafly]</i>
<i>Hey, I wish 'em luck,</i>
<i>you know what I mean?</i>

228
00:14:12,385 --> 00:14:14,921
<i>[Sal from the Bronx]</i>
<i>Yeah, right. What good's</i>
<i>luck gonna do 'em?</i>

229
00:14:14,921 --> 00:14:18,191
Wasn't exactly
a great pre-season, Joe.
Pre-season's for football.

230
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:21,694
It's spring training,
that's all it is.
Not any more, Joe.

231
00:14:21,694 --> 00:14:24,430
So, are the Yankees
ready for the season?

232
00:14:24,430 --> 00:14:27,500
Well, we're about
to find out, aren't we?

233
00:14:29,302 --> 00:14:31,170
[crowd groans]
<i>[Radio announcer]</i>
<i>You're on!</i>

234
00:14:31,170 --> 00:14:33,339
<i>[Caller]</i>
<i>Twenty-one games,</i>
<i>they lost ten.</i>

235
00:14:33,339 --> 00:14:35,675
<i>They can't pick up the ball,</i>
<i>they don't know</i>
<i>where to throw it,</i>

236
00:14:35,675 --> 00:14:39,378
<i>no pitching, no hitting--</i>
<i>they lucky they haven't</i>
<i>lost all of them!</i>

237
00:14:40,713 --> 00:14:43,916
[crowd booing]

238
00:14:45,451 --> 00:14:47,320
I left my purse
out there on the field.

239
00:14:47,320 --> 00:14:49,689
Focus, man.

240
00:14:49,689 --> 00:14:52,592
They're pretty upset, Joe.
Better talk to 'em.

241
00:14:54,193 --> 00:14:56,262
[bats clattering]

242
00:15:02,502 --> 00:15:05,404
How's your arm, Doc?

243
00:15:05,404 --> 00:15:08,541
It's fine, and you?
Good. Real good.

244
00:15:08,541 --> 00:15:10,543
We'll get it back.

245
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,349
Paulie?

246
00:15:16,349 --> 00:15:17,683
Yeah?

247
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:20,186
You played some
football in college, right?

248
00:15:20,186 --> 00:15:22,522
Yeah, some.

249
00:15:22,522 --> 00:15:25,591
How many games
in a football season?

250
00:15:25,591 --> 00:15:29,295
Twelve.

251
00:15:29,295 --> 00:15:30,997
How many games
in a baseball season?

252
00:15:30,997 --> 00:15:33,266
A hundred and sixty-two.

253
00:15:39,739 --> 00:15:43,476
Joe's right, boys.
We got more games,
let's get the focus back!

254
00:15:43,476 --> 00:15:45,011
Let's dig in!

255
00:15:45,011 --> 00:15:46,779
[smattering of applause]
[chattering]

256
00:15:46,779 --> 00:15:48,314
Come on!

257
00:15:48,314 --> 00:15:51,017
Joe? Joe.
Telephone.

258
00:15:51,017 --> 00:15:52,618
Yeah, would you tell him
I'll call him back, Zim?

259
00:15:52,618 --> 00:15:54,954
Joe, it's George.

260
00:16:12,038 --> 00:16:13,439
<i> [Steinbrenner]</i>
<i> How ya doin', Joe?</i>

261
00:16:13,439 --> 00:16:15,508
Uh, fine, George.

262
00:16:15,508 --> 00:16:17,376
Well, this is one of those
I thought we could win,

263
00:16:17,376 --> 00:16:19,245
<i> but sometimes they</i>
<i> just get away from ya.</i>

264
00:16:19,245 --> 00:16:20,780
No, no, no, I meant
you, your family.

265
00:16:20,780 --> 00:16:23,382
You settled in,
got a nice place?

266
00:16:23,382 --> 00:16:25,418
<i> Lovely place.</i>
And there are no problems,

267
00:16:25,418 --> 00:16:27,486
because, uh,
if there are...

268
00:16:27,486 --> 00:16:30,590
No, not at all, George.
<i> And no distractions,</i>

269
00:16:30,590 --> 00:16:32,592
<i> I mean, nothing is</i>
<i> preying on your mind?</i>

270
00:16:32,592 --> 00:16:35,528
Nothing.
<i> Well, that's all I want</i>
<i> to know, Joe.</i>

271
00:16:38,798 --> 00:16:41,801
[beeps]
You know what's wrong.
We haven't got any hitters!

272
00:16:41,801 --> 00:16:44,403
You're the trading genius.
Why can't you get me
any hitters?

273
00:16:44,403 --> 00:16:46,606
We've got hitters,
Mr. Steinbrenner.
That's not the problem.

274
00:16:46,606 --> 00:16:49,575
If you're looking for 
an area where you want
to make personnel changes,

275
00:16:49,575 --> 00:16:51,844
you've got to consider the fact
that in our last four losses,

276
00:16:51,844 --> 00:16:54,080
we gave up six, seven,
eight, and ten runs!

277
00:16:54,080 --> 00:16:56,449
Unless we get some
pitching help, we've got
to find some hitters!

278
00:16:56,449 --> 00:16:59,385
If you're gonna give up
that many runs, you got
to score runs!

279
00:16:59,385 --> 00:17:01,120
A lot of them!

280
00:17:03,122 --> 00:17:05,124
Where's all
these olives come from?
Are these Greek olives,

281
00:17:05,124 --> 00:17:06,559
or Italian ones?
[Woman] No, no, no, no.
Italian.

282
00:17:06,559 --> 00:17:07,827
These are Italian olives.
You sure?

283
00:17:07,827 --> 00:17:10,563
Has it got a lot
of salt in there?
Kalamata?

284
00:17:10,563 --> 00:17:13,099
All right,
what's this all about?

285
00:17:13,099 --> 00:17:14,800
Beats the hell out of me.
I didn't call this meeting.

286
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:17,436
Joey, this is
not a meeting.

287
00:17:17,436 --> 00:17:19,605
All right,
so it's not a meeting.
But what's it all about?

288
00:17:19,605 --> 00:17:21,307
Yeah, Rae.
What is it all about?

289
00:17:21,307 --> 00:17:24,110
It's about your brother.
Frank? What did he do?

290
00:17:24,110 --> 00:17:27,747
He didn't do anything.
Why isn't he here?

291
00:17:27,747 --> 00:17:29,815
He's in Florida!

292
00:17:29,815 --> 00:17:33,586
Exactly... and
why is he in Florida?

293
00:17:33,586 --> 00:17:35,621
Uh, because he lives there?

294
00:17:35,621 --> 00:17:38,691
[laughs]
With his brother managing
a baseball team

295
00:17:38,691 --> 00:17:41,427
practically across
the street from where
he has an apartment!

296
00:17:41,427 --> 00:17:43,729
He doesn't want to get
in my hair! It's very
thoughtful of him.

297
00:17:43,729 --> 00:17:46,899
A-Are we talking about
the same brother here?
Come on, please!

298
00:17:46,899 --> 00:17:49,635
Ah, this is crazy.
Come on, hey,
gimme a break!

299
00:17:49,635 --> 00:17:51,804
So pick up the phone,
and ask him why he's there!
Yeah!

300
00:17:51,804 --> 00:17:55,508
You guys, listen
to your sister.

301
00:17:57,710 --> 00:17:59,345
[Rae]
Thank you.

302
00:17:59,345 --> 00:18:01,480
Now, Frankie lives
for baseball, right?

303
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:03,549
Yeah.
Every time there's a game,

304
00:18:03,549 --> 00:18:06,152
he calls you
whether you are playing,
whether you are managing,

305
00:18:06,152 --> 00:18:08,654
whether you are broadcasting--
whatever, right?

306
00:18:09,755 --> 00:18:12,391
Has he been calling you?

307
00:18:12,391 --> 00:18:14,594
No.

308
00:18:18,898 --> 00:18:23,369
How soon can you go?
Soon as is humanly possible.

309
00:18:25,504 --> 00:18:27,773
[booing]

310
00:18:34,947 --> 00:18:37,650
Let's call it
a night, Doc.

311
00:18:37,650 --> 00:18:39,752
Don't know what's the matter.
The ball's straight.

312
00:18:39,752 --> 00:18:42,955
Stays up.
It's a long road.

313
00:18:42,955 --> 00:18:44,790
We're gonna need you.

314
00:18:57,670 --> 00:18:59,739
He'll come around.

315
00:19:08,214 --> 00:19:10,416
[knocks]
Joe?

316
00:19:10,416 --> 00:19:12,718
Doc! Come on in,
have a seat, will you?

317
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:25,431
Doc, it's only temporary
until you get it worked out,

318
00:19:25,431 --> 00:19:27,566
but for now, I got to
pull you out of the rotation.

319
00:19:27,566 --> 00:19:30,836
You'll work out of
the bullpen for a while,
low pressure situations,

320
00:19:30,836 --> 00:19:33,572
it'll come around.

321
00:19:36,242 --> 00:19:38,778
You know, I--

322
00:19:38,778 --> 00:19:42,715
I have eighteen long months
to think about how bad
I screwed up my life,

323
00:19:42,715 --> 00:19:46,452
you know,
I let my dad down,

324
00:19:46,452 --> 00:19:48,854
and when I got that
suspension letter--

325
00:19:48,854 --> 00:19:50,589
You know, I just kind
of bottomed out,

326
00:19:50,589 --> 00:19:52,758
I really got down,
and I was just kind of numb.

327
00:19:52,758 --> 00:19:54,860
Then I said to myself,
"I can make it back."

328
00:19:54,860 --> 00:19:57,863
You are back.
You're in the major leagues.

329
00:19:57,863 --> 00:19:59,932
You just gotta do
a little more work.

330
00:19:59,932 --> 00:20:03,035
I threw all last year, Joe.

331
00:20:03,035 --> 00:20:08,474
I threw all winter,
getting ready to come back,
and my arm is fine, Joe.

332
00:20:08,474 --> 00:20:10,810
It's just um...

333
00:20:10,810 --> 00:20:13,979
It's just--

334
00:20:13,979 --> 00:20:17,483
Just--
It's just not there.

335
00:20:18,751 --> 00:20:22,888
Don't give up.
Don't give up on yourself.

336
00:20:32,832 --> 00:20:35,801
Hey, Joe. Come here.

337
00:20:35,801 --> 00:20:37,770
I want you
to see something.

338
00:20:39,605 --> 00:20:42,641
This is Doc in '85,
and this is him now.

339
00:20:42,641 --> 00:20:44,977
Now, I been looking at these
over and over again,

340
00:20:44,977 --> 00:20:46,912
tryin' to see
what's different.

341
00:20:46,912 --> 00:20:49,648
I can't find anything.

342
00:20:51,750 --> 00:20:55,688
Yeah.

343
00:20:55,688 --> 00:20:57,790
I don't know what
the problem is, Joe.

344
00:20:57,790 --> 00:21:00,326
Well, maybe
that's the problem.

345
00:21:00,326 --> 00:21:04,029
He is trying to do
what he did when he was 21.

346
00:21:04,029 --> 00:21:07,767
Can you imagine if
we tried to do the stuff
that we did when we were 21?

347
00:21:07,767 --> 00:21:10,536
[grunts]
Good night.
Get some sleep, pal.

348
00:21:12,605 --> 00:21:14,740
Yeah.

349
00:21:30,055 --> 00:21:32,591
Hey, Doc?

350
00:21:32,591 --> 00:21:34,360
Like you to try something.

351
00:21:34,360 --> 00:21:36,729
I want to see if
we can eliminate some of
the parts of your motion.

352
00:21:36,729 --> 00:21:38,697
Like, simplify it.

353
00:21:38,697 --> 00:21:40,699
Bring your hands up slowly.

354
00:21:41,734 --> 00:21:43,836
No, no, no.
Not that high. Down.

355
00:21:43,836 --> 00:21:46,372
Good, good.
Now pull back a bit.

356
00:21:46,372 --> 00:21:49,375
All right.
You okay there?
Mm-hmm.

357
00:21:49,375 --> 00:21:51,610
All right.
Try a couple.

358
00:21:56,115 --> 00:21:58,817
How'd that feel?

359
00:21:58,817 --> 00:22:01,053
Good.
Good?

360
00:22:01,053 --> 00:22:03,856
[laughs]
All right, here.
There you go.

361
00:22:05,391 --> 00:22:07,626
Throw a couple more.

362
00:22:17,903 --> 00:22:19,338
Oh!

363
00:22:37,056 --> 00:22:39,925
Hey, Frankie.
Hey, Rae!

364
00:22:39,925 --> 00:22:41,827
How are ya?
[laughs]

365
00:22:41,827 --> 00:22:44,163
I got a little dizzy
for a second. I'm fine.

366
00:22:44,163 --> 00:22:45,164
Oh!
You all right?

367
00:22:45,164 --> 00:22:47,800
Yeah, hey. No problem.
Hey!

368
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:49,668
Come on, let's get
a cup of coffee.

369
00:22:49,668 --> 00:22:51,036
How are you?
I'm good.

370
00:22:51,036 --> 00:22:53,072
You look beautiful.
You always look beautiful.

371
00:22:53,072 --> 00:22:55,007
Ahh!
Well, you do. Come on!

372
00:22:55,007 --> 00:22:58,811
[cheering]

373
00:22:58,811 --> 00:23:01,847
<i>[Announcer]</i>
<i>It'll be a 2-2 to Tartabull.</i>
<i>Struck him out swinging!</i>

374
00:23:01,847 --> 00:23:03,816
<i>Breaking ball away!</i>
<i>Well, Coney's been great today.</i>

375
00:23:03,816 --> 00:23:05,985
<i> I think that's gonna</i>
<i> do it for him.</i>

376
00:23:05,985 --> 00:23:08,921
<i> Ends with 12 strikeouts!</i>
<i> He looked phenomenal</i>
<i> today out there.</i>

377
00:23:11,790 --> 00:23:14,159
Great game, Coney.

378
00:23:14,159 --> 00:23:17,463
I don't know where
we would be without you.

379
00:23:17,463 --> 00:23:19,932
How long has
this been this way?
Not long, Joe.

380
00:23:19,932 --> 00:23:22,935
What does that
feel like?

381
00:23:22,935 --> 00:23:25,771
It's okay. Doesn't hurt.

382
00:23:25,771 --> 00:23:29,742
Which is it?
Doesn't hurt? Or okay?

383
00:23:29,742 --> 00:23:32,044
What do you mean?

384
00:23:32,044 --> 00:23:33,946
Can you feel
what I'm doing?

385
00:23:33,946 --> 00:23:36,015
Yeah, you're moving
my fingers.

386
00:23:36,015 --> 00:23:38,017
Honest answer, Coney.

387
00:23:42,488 --> 00:23:44,056
[sighs]

388
00:23:44,056 --> 00:23:46,225
After about
the fourth inning or so,

389
00:23:46,225 --> 00:23:48,227
sometimes later, I guess,

390
00:23:48,227 --> 00:23:50,829
I can't feel
my fingers at all.

391
00:23:50,829 --> 00:23:52,965
So this isn't
the first time it's happened.

392
00:23:52,965 --> 00:23:57,036
Last couple of games.
Goes away in about an hour.

393
00:23:57,036 --> 00:23:59,705
I shook his hand.
It was ice.

394
00:24:10,883 --> 00:24:13,018
Ready, Joe.

395
00:24:20,893 --> 00:24:24,863
I must have done something
right in a previous life.

396
00:24:24,863 --> 00:24:27,199
I have never seen
two more beautiful women.

397
00:24:30,269 --> 00:24:33,138
Did you hear that?
I guess he likes your dress.

398
00:24:34,840 --> 00:24:36,875
[chuckling]

399
00:24:36,875 --> 00:24:39,745
What were you thinking about?

400
00:24:39,745 --> 00:24:41,113
When?

401
00:24:41,113 --> 00:24:44,750
Just now.
When I walked in.

402
00:24:44,750 --> 00:24:46,218
You looked so lost.

403
00:24:46,218 --> 00:24:50,322
Well, I was lost,
and then you came in,

404
00:24:50,322 --> 00:24:52,558
and how could I be lost?

405
00:24:52,558 --> 00:24:55,994
[coos]
Aw.

406
00:24:55,994 --> 00:24:58,063
That's such
a beautiful thing to say.

407
00:24:58,063 --> 00:25:00,299
I read it somewhere.
[chuckles]

408
00:25:00,299 --> 00:25:02,534
[laughing]

409
00:25:08,207 --> 00:25:11,176
[phone ringing]

410
00:25:14,046 --> 00:25:15,914
[yawns]

411
00:25:16,915 --> 00:25:18,050
Hello?

412
00:25:18,050 --> 00:25:19,351
<i> Ali, it's Rae.</i>

413
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:21,353
<i> Is Joe there?</i>
<i> Can I talk to him?</i>

414
00:25:21,353 --> 00:25:24,123
Um, well,
he's still sleeping.

415
00:25:24,123 --> 00:25:26,024
He didn't get in
till 2:00 a.m.

416
00:25:26,024 --> 00:25:28,227
I hate to wake him up.
He's not been
sleeping very well.

417
00:25:28,227 --> 00:25:31,196
It's kind of important, Ali.

418
00:25:33,832 --> 00:25:36,168
Okay.

419
00:25:36,168 --> 00:25:37,803
Joe?

420
00:25:37,803 --> 00:25:39,872
It's Rae.
She says it's important.

421
00:25:39,872 --> 00:25:42,141
What?
It's Rae.
She's on the phone.

422
00:25:42,141 --> 00:25:43,609
Oh.

423
00:25:46,078 --> 00:25:48,080
Hello, Rae.
What's the matter?

424
00:25:49,948 --> 00:25:52,351
Frank's sick.

425
00:25:52,351 --> 00:25:56,288
He won't go see a doctor,
and I can't get him
to do anything about it.

426
00:25:56,288 --> 00:25:58,624
Put him on.

427
00:25:58,624 --> 00:26:00,292
<i> He does not know</i>
<i> that I'm calling you.</i>

428
00:26:00,292 --> 00:26:01,960
It's okay.
Put him on.

429
00:26:01,960 --> 00:26:03,962
Oh.

430
00:26:09,101 --> 00:26:10,836
Frank?
Hmm?

431
00:26:10,836 --> 00:26:12,838
It's Joe.
He wants to talk to you.

432
00:26:12,838 --> 00:26:13,972
Ohh.

433
00:26:13,972 --> 00:26:15,974
This another one
of your brainstorms?

434
00:26:15,974 --> 00:26:18,077
What brainstorms?
This is your brother.

435
00:26:18,077 --> 00:26:20,078
Your brother who loves you?

436
00:26:20,078 --> 00:26:21,980
He wants to talk to you.

437
00:26:21,980 --> 00:26:23,415
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

438
00:26:23,415 --> 00:26:25,417
Hey, Joe, how you doing?

439
00:26:25,417 --> 00:26:27,252
Go to a doctor.

440
00:26:27,252 --> 00:26:29,888
<i> Yeah. Hey, how about</i>
<i> that game last night, huh?</i>

441
00:26:29,888 --> 00:26:32,658
This Cone--
hell of a pitcher.

442
00:26:32,658 --> 00:26:34,893
Where the hell would you be
without him?

443
00:26:34,893 --> 00:26:37,663
Well, we're about to find out.
He's got a problem
with his hand.

444
00:26:37,663 --> 00:26:41,033
Yeah? Is it serious?

445
00:26:41,033 --> 00:26:43,869
<i> I don't know if it's serious,</i>

446
00:26:43,869 --> 00:26:46,305
<i> but I do know that he's got</i>
<i> enough sense to go</i>
<i> and see a doctor.</i>

447
00:26:46,305 --> 00:26:48,307
What are you doing, Frank?

448
00:26:48,307 --> 00:26:50,342
What the hell are you doing?

449
00:26:50,342 --> 00:26:52,344
Hey, Joey, thanks.

450
00:26:52,344 --> 00:26:55,881
I really appreciate it.
I'm busy right now.

451
00:26:55,881 --> 00:26:57,382
What the--
<i> Bye.</i>

452
00:26:57,382 --> 00:26:59,051
I love ya.

453
00:27:05,090 --> 00:27:07,159
[sighs]

454
00:27:07,159 --> 00:27:08,994
[players chattering]
Fellas.

455
00:27:08,994 --> 00:27:11,296
Everybody, listen up.

456
00:27:12,898 --> 00:27:15,367
Joe's got something
he needs to tell ya.

457
00:27:15,367 --> 00:27:17,903
All right.
First things first.

458
00:27:17,903 --> 00:27:20,439
I want you to hear it from me
before you hear it
from anybody else.

459
00:27:20,439 --> 00:27:22,207
Coney needs surgery.

460
00:27:22,207 --> 00:27:24,009
Oh, come on.

461
00:27:24,009 --> 00:27:26,912
He's got an aneurysm
in his pitching shoulder.

462
00:27:26,912 --> 00:27:30,249
We hear "aneurysm,"
we get scared,
but it's not like that.

463
00:27:30,249 --> 00:27:32,484
It's not life-threatening.
He's gonna have
the surgery this week,

464
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:34,486
and it's all gonna
get taken care of,

465
00:27:34,486 --> 00:27:37,489
so we have nothing
to worry about on that score.

466
00:27:37,489 --> 00:27:40,158
I think I only
have to say this once,

467
00:27:40,158 --> 00:27:42,361
'cause I know you all know it.

468
00:27:42,361 --> 00:27:45,264
This is a 25-man game.

469
00:27:45,264 --> 00:27:49,067
Will it be harder to win
without Coney? Absolutely.

470
00:27:49,067 --> 00:27:52,938
Which means each
and every one of you
has to pull that much harder.

471
00:27:52,938 --> 00:27:54,940
So let's not waste
time and energy

472
00:27:54,940 --> 00:27:57,376
lamenting on
what we don't have.

